#Text=Teaneck
#Text=Teaneck is a township in Bergen County , New Jersey .
#Text=It is the suburb with the second highest population of the 70 towns in the county with 39,776 as of the 2010 United States Census .
#Text=The town is 11 miles west of New York City .
#Text=Teaneck was founded on February 19 , 1895 .
#Text=Today , it has a diverse population .
#Text=Teaneck has many lovely streets for its residents and visitors to stroll , shop , dine , and even enjoy local artwork .
#Text=Understand
#Text=You will more than likely need a car to get around .
#Text=If you work in New York City , however , you can easily take a bus ride .
#Text=Public transportation is fairly easy to figure out and buses run very frequently in and out of the town ’s limits .
#Text=Just like New York , summers are hot and sticky with temperatures rising into the 90s .
#Text=The usual summer temperatures range from 69-85 ° F ( 21-29 ° C ) , and the winter months usually range from as high as 38 degrees to as low as .
#Text=The tri-state area shares a very similar range in temperature and they take pleasure in all four seasons .

#Text=The town is known for its major institutions like Holy Name Medical Hospital and the Metropolitan Campus of Farleigh Dickinson University , the largest private university in the state of New Jersey .
#Text=The Teaneck Armory is home to the New Jersey National Guard ’s 50th Main Support Battalion and they host many events for the community , mainly in the summer months .
#Text=The commercial development of the town is concentrated in four main shopping areas and there is convenient access to many main highways from different points in town .
#Text=By car
#Text=Teaneck is positioned along a number of major highways , including the New Jersey Turnpike ( a portion of I-95 ) and I-80 .
#Text=Teaneck is the eastern final point of I-80 , which stretches around west to downtown San Francisco , California .
#Text=The town ’s main highway is Route 4 , running east to west through Teaneck from New York .

#Text=There is no commercial development along this highway in the town itself due to a decision taken back in the 1940s to create a greenbelt , but there is easy access to the commercial area just a few minutes down Route 4 .
#Text=New Jersey ’s other main route is the Garden State Parkway , which can be reached by car just a few miles west of Teaneck .
#Text=By plane
#Text=The closest commercial airport to Teaneck in New Jersey is Newark Liberty International Airport , away in Newark .
#Text=New York City ’s LaGuardia Airport is miles away in Queens and can be accessed via the George Washington Bridge and is approximately 22 minutes away ( in the most ideal traffic conditions ) .
#Text=John F. Kennedy International Airport in Queens is ( 34 minutes ) from Teaneck .
#Text=There is also Teterboro Airport ( TEB ) , which offers general aviation service , and is about ( 10 minutes ) away .
#Text=All of these airports can be accessed by car or by taxi services located in Teaneck that will pick you up any time , day or night .
#Text=By bus
#Text=New Jersey Transit bus service has very frequent service to Teaneck Road , Route 4 , and Cedar Lane .
#Text=There is less frequent service on other main streets .
#Text=NJTransit bus services are offered at the Port Authority Bus Terminal in Midtown Manhattan via the 155 , 157 , 167 , and 168 routes .
#Text=There is service to and from the George Washington Bridge Bus Terminal in Upper Manhattan via the 171 , 175 , 178 , and 186 routes .

#Text=A number of jitney services also provide an inexpensive , fast unscheduled service along Route 4 between Paterson and the George Washington Bridge Bus Terminal , with stops along the way including several in Teaneck .
#Text=By train
#Text=There is no passenger train operation in Teaneck .
#Text=See and do
#Text=Teaneck has four main shopping areas located on Cedar Lane , Teaneck Road , DeGraw Avenue , West Englewood Avenue , and Queen Anne Road , most commonly known as " The Plaza . "
#Text=Cedar Lane .
#Text=One of the more popular and conveniently located streets is one of the busiest streets in town .
#Text=There are over 15 restaurants , clothing stores , shoe stores , salons , and the Cedar Lane Cinemas .
#Text=It is the town ’s only movie theater and they occasionally host live performances by local performance groups .
#Text=Many restaurant on the street are Kosher .
#Text=A farmers ' market is held every week , even into the winter months , and has become one of the most popular events in town .
#Text=Free dance lessons are also given outdoors in the summer months as a community outreach program to bring people of all ages and backgrounds together .
#Text=Teaneck Road .
#Text=This is another popular street for residents to shop for the essentials without having to get on any highways .
#Text=This road stretches all the way through town , connecting Teaneck to its bordering towns .
#Text=There is also direct access to the highway from many points on this road .
#Text=West Englewood Avenue .

#Text=The west portion of this street stretches from the train tracks all the way down to the Hackensack River and is mostly residential , but east of the tracks , the street is part of the Queen Anne Road " Plaza " business district and is lined with restaurants and shops .
#Text=Queen Anne Road ( “ The Plaza ” ) .
#Text=This is the most popular road in town next to Cedar Lane because of its diversity .
#Text=There is something for every demographic , whether it is a Kosher chain of places to eat , a bank , a pharmacy , and the most popular restaurant in town Mexicali Blues Café .
#Text=Live bands will come and play at the café once or twice a month and the place will stay open until well passed two in the morning .
#Text=The younger crowd tends to hang out down there , but up the road is referred to as “ The Plaza ” where families gather .

#Text=Several Kosher eateries are found in the area where families can go and have their choice of pizza , falafel , chicken , bagels , pasta , chinese , sushi , Persian , Italian , burgers , salads , and even a Starbucks-like coffee house .
#Text=Parks
#Text=For its size , Teaneck has quite a few parks , 7 to be exact .
#Text=They are mostly small grassy spaces in residential areas with swing sets and basketball courts , but there are a few that hold significance for the entire town .
#Text=Andreas Park .
#Text=West Englewood Avenue will lead you down the hill to this park that sits on the edge of the Hackensack River .
#Text=This park has large open space , a jungle gym and free public tennis courts .
#Text=This park is active year round with a great spot for people to push off in their boats to drift on the Hackensack River .
#Text=Votee Park .
#Text=The largest completely developed park in Teaneck and is located almost right in the middle of town .
#Text=The park covers a huge amount of space , covering an area between Queen Anne Road and Palisade Avenue .

#Text=Facilities include an in-ground swimming pool , a children ’s wading pool , restrooms , an amphitheater , three soccer fields , five baseball fields , refreshment stands , a double handball court , four tennis courts , and a lighted , enclosed , two court basketball facility .
#Text=There are 2 playgrounds ( at either end ) , picnic areas , and paved walking paths .
#Text=One playground is accessible for disabled children and has special equipment designed for kids with physical disabilities .
